## 2. Political and Institutional Impact

### 2.1 Artificial States and Political Instability

Colonial borders were often arbitrarily drawn without regard for ethnic, cultural, or linguistic realities, creating "artificial states" prone to internal conflict ([Caldwell, 2017](https://medium.com/@megancaldwell/the-effects-of-colonization-how-it-happened-and-how-it-still-continues-7e1a5a0f4e2c); [GraduateWay, 2017](https://graduateway.com/ways-colonialism-still-impact-today/)). This has led to civil wars, secessionist movements, and ongoing political instability in regions such as Africa and the Middle East.

### 2.2 Direct vs. Indirect Colonial Rule and Institutional Quality

Research indicates that the form of colonial rule—direct or indirect—has long-term effects on postcolonial governance. Direct rule, characterized by centralized bureaucratic institutions, tends to leave more effective governance legacies, while indirect rule, which empowered local chiefs and decentralized authority, often resulted in weak state institutions and "decentralized despotism" ([Lange, 2004](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.worlddev.2003.12.001)).

| Aspect                   | Direct Rule                          | Indirect Rule                         |
|--------------------------|------------------------------------|-------------------------------------|
| Governance Structure     | Centralized, bureaucratic           | Decentralized, patrimonial          |
| Legal System             | Formal, European law-based          | Customary law, localized            |
| State Capacity           | Higher infrastructural power        | Limited state control                |
| Postcolonial Stability   | Generally higher                    | Often lower, prone to instability   |

### 2.3 Democracy and Political Development

Indirect rule correlates negatively with democratization and political stability. Former British colonies with extensive indirect rule show lower levels of bureaucratic effectiveness, rule of law, and political stability decades after independence ([Lange, 2004](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.worlddev.2003.12.001)).

### 2.4 Case Studies: Democratic Republic of Congo and Cuba

- **DRC**: Belgian colonialism's brutal exploitation and refusal to integrate Africans into governance left the country politically fragmented and unstable post-independence ([Caldwell, 2017](https://medium.com/@megancaldwell/the-effects-of-colonization-how-it-happened-and-how-it-still-continues-7e1a5a0f4e2c)).

- **Cuba**: Spanish colonization followed by U.S. neo-colonial economic control created dependency and political interference, shaping Cuba’s modern political economy ([Caldwell, 2017](https://medium.com/@megancaldwell/the-effects-of-colonization-how-it-happened-and-how-it-still-continues-7e1a5a0f4e2c)).

